d Distribution: Analytical (III) -- tLECTURE 21. Overall Equilibrium -- tLECTURE 22. International Trade -- tLECTURE 23. John Stuart Mill -- tD. OTHER MID-NINETEENTH-CENTURY THOUGHT -- tLECTURE 24. Mill (cont.)—Saint-Simon and Marx -- tLECTURE 25. Marx (cont.)—List and the Historical School -- tE. BEGINNINGS OF MODERN ANALYSIS -- tLECTURE 26. The Historical School (cont.)—Precursors of Change: Cournot, von Thünen, and Rae -- tLECTURE 27. The Marginal Revolution (I): Jevons -- tLECTURE 28. The Marginal Revolution (II): Jevons and Menger -- tLECTURE 29. The Marginal Revolution (III): Costs (Wieser)—The Pricing of Factor Services (Wieser, Clark, Wicksteed) -- tLECTURE 30 Capital Theory: Böhm-Bawerk and Fisher -- tLECTURE 31. Walras—Pareto -- tLECTURE 32. Marshall -- tLECTURE 33. Money: Fisher, Marshall, Wicksell -- tAFTERWORD The Further Evolution of the Subject -- tAPPENDIX A. Robbins’ Reading List -- tAPPENDIX B. Robbins’ Writings in the History of Economic Thought -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLionel Robbins's now famous lectures on the history of economic thought comprise one of the greatest accounts since World War II of the evolution of economic ideas. This volume represents the first time those lectures have been published. Lord Robbins (1898-1984) was a remarkably accomplished thinker, writer, and public figure. He made important contributions to economic theory, methodology, and policy analysis, directed the economic section of Winston Churchill's War Cabinet, and served as chairman of the Financial Times. As a historian of economic ideas, he ranks with Joseph Schumpeter and Jacob Viner as one of the foremost scholars of the century. These lectures, delivered at the London School of Economics between 1979 and 1981 and tape-recorded by Robbins's grandson, display his mastery of the intellectual history of economics, his infectious enthusiasm for the subject, and his eloquence and incisive wit. They cover a broad chronological range, beginning with Plato, Aristotle, and Aquinas, focusing extensively on Adam Smith, Thomas Malthus and the classicals, and finishing with a discussion of moderns and marginalists from Marx to Alfred Marshall. Robbins takes a varied and inclusive approach to intellectual history. As he says in his first lecture: "I shall go my own sweet way--sometimes talk about doctrine, sometimes talk about persons, sometimes talk about periods." The lectures are united by Robbins's conviction that it is impossible to understand adequately contemporary institutions and social sciences without understanding the ideas behind their development. Authoritative yet accessible, combining the immediacy of the spoken word with Robbins's exceptional talent for clear, well-organized exposition, this volume will be welcomed by anyone interested in the intellectual origins of the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aBaumol, William J.1 aBaumol, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMedema, Steven G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSamuels, Warren J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082279940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400822799423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400822799.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aE